text: Okay. Okay. We're rolling. Okay. I am very unknowledgeable about collectors, so some of the questions I'm going to ask you are pretty basic. All right. That's fine. I assume many of your listeners will be the same. Right. Exactly. Okay. The first question is a pretty obvious one. Can you just briefly tell me how you got started as a collector? Well, I guess we have to go back quite a ways. I got interested in science fiction in high school, as many people do. And once I started finding that, hey, out there in the big world, they have newsstands that sell books, boy, I bought everything that I could get my hands on for many, many years, and I really got started as a serious collector, however. I have my wife to thank for that, and she sort of wishes she hadn't said it sometimes, I think, because I was telling her about the books that I'd read when I was in high school, which happened to be a series of hardcover juvenile science fiction books published by the Winston Company, and how I'd been in love with those things, had read them several times, and had fondled them a lot, and so on, and she says, oh, there are used book dealers. They could probably find copies of those, and you could buy them, and I hadn't even considered that In the past, I'd only bought what I'd found at newsstands. And so when the time came and I started sending these lists to all the dealers, well, they had all these other fantastic books also. And it sort of mushroomed from there. Okay, good. Could you tell me what kinds of things you concentrate on collecting? Well, I once gave a talk on this subject, and I titled it The Complete Science Fiction Collector, Confessions of a Pack Rat. In other words, I'm very, very versatile and Catholic in my tastes. I don't like all kinds of things as much, equally, but I collect anything that's published in the science fiction and fantasy vein, I get my hands on, and then I can afford which means almost. I've got copies of almost every book that's been published. Okay, and I'm not sure I still understand that. I'm not sure if there's a term for this, but I'm talking about categories like paperbacks, pulps, hardbacks, things of that sort. I started out with paperbacks and the Digest magazines. I've gone back in terms of picking up the old pulp magazines to the point where now I have almost all of them that were ever published, starting back with Weird Tales in 1923 and Amazing Stories in 1926. I'm very proud of my complete collection of weird tales since I understand there's only about 30 copies or so in existence and just about as good on astounding science fiction, for example. Recently, I have been branching out into hardbacks also, but I'm a long, long ways from complete on that. What about this plain old paperback? Well, I have about 14,000, 15,000. Is that enough for you? Yeah. Do you try to pick up all of those, or do you just take certain kinds? There's always a problem in making the, where do you draw the line? But I basically get everything that's clearly science fiction, everything that's clearly fantasy. I kind of draw the line someplace in the horror vein to one side and maybe fairy tales on the other side, And sometimes I'll draw the line at, you know, an Adam Baum story that's in the near future or something like that. But basically, I get every paper bag in science fiction and fantasy. In multiple editions, I might say, every time a new cover comes out, why I'll buy the new edition. Okay. Now, this question is really going to show my ignorance, but how do you accumulate your books? Do you go about it by cold, methodical planning and then go right to the publisher, or do you just search around bookstores? How do you go about that? No, I buy most of mine these days used. I'll buy the ones I like better, new, so that I have a mint copy on paperbacks especially. But an awful lot of them I buy them used. They're fairly recent, just in the local bookstores. Lubbock is blessed with about seven or eight, so I make the rounds on a regular basis and just pick up whatever I happen to come across. Sooner or later, I find most everything in the recent things. And on older things, I go through mail-order dealers. Okay, then you, I assume, and I know through Bill that there are publications and so forth. I mean, do you, how do you know how much is coming out? Do you have some kind of checklist? The best source by far is the news magazine of science fiction called Locus. and Science Fiction Chronicle also has these sort of things. They attempt to list every book that comes out in the field. In fact, they're even wider in their categories than I am and they include academic-type books and things like this, too. And every month they will list everything that's come out by every publisher. Most of the publishers send them copies and the ones that don't, they still will write down there that they know this book exists, that they haven't seen a copy. They also give mini-reviews on many of them. And I assume for the—I call it Pulps. I'm not sure what the term is. I assume for those, you just have subscriptions? There are no pulp magazines that have been published since 1955 or so. They sort of went the way of the dinosaurs. But their successors are the Digest-sized magazines, as well as such large, oversized ones as Omni and Twilight Zone, currently. And so I buy those on the newsstands every month. Okay. Do you ever run across any valuable finds or little nuggets just by accident, just browsing around? Not as many as I would like. Occasionally I do I pick up quite a few You know moderately rare things Say for example For half a cover price At a used bookstore But that's getting to be more and more rare As the collectors have got all the valuable things Grabbed up Most of them I have to pay More or less market value Actually one other source I didn't mention For many of my books Because I buy so many I'll actually buy a person's entire collection just to get the books that I especially want if there's some older, rarer ones among them. I assume, then, you have a complete set of the Ace Doubles? Actually, I'm still missing one that's been rather elusive. But other than that, I have all the Ace Doubles, yeah. Is that D13? I have a D13. Yes, I do. I was very lucky to get that before the prices started escalating as much as they have. And I got it from one of the major dealers, and I paid what now, three or four years later, would seem to be a real steal. Okay, what about traveling? Do you ever travel just to make collecting trips? No, I combine collecting trips with whenever I happen to be traveling. I remember one time, not too long ago, we visited relatives in Madison, Wisconsin, and I had to mail all the books back because there wasn't room in the rabbit for the family in the books. And my wife said, no way are we going to sit in here with several boxes of books. But I don't make deliberate trips just to buy things. Okay. Are you a reader and a fan of science fiction first and then a collector, or are you in the field principally for collecting? Yeah, people keep asking me that. How much of this stuff do you read? Well, the answer is as much as I have time for, which in my rather busy schedule is between 50 and 70 books a year, I estimate. And I'll probably add 1,000 to the collection in a year, so I certainly don't read a very big percentage. But I pick and choose among what I've got. Since I have less hardbacks, and since they cost more in general, I feel some sort of a semi-obligation to try to read something if I bought in hardback. okay I'm sure you're asked this question from people who know that you're a collector just from a psychological point of view why do you collect because it's there that's that's actually I suppose a difficult question for anyone to answer first of all you have to love books or whatever you're collecting this is the collector's mania there's lots of people that collect anything from match books to old Avon bottles, for heaven's sakes, and I collect what I enjoy from other standpoints. I enjoy the artwork on them, I enjoy reading the things, I like to read at least the representative's book by any author that's important in the field and so on, and I just love books. All you're concerned about is getting a copy of every one. Why science fiction books? Why not something else, like mysteries or westerns or seashells or something? Because I love science fiction. Something we haven't gotten into the conversation yet is, here at Texas Tech, I also am involved in helping the team teach the course in science fiction. We have a special course through our honors program, and there are three or four of us every semester. The team teaches this thing to a small group, and we try to teach some principles about writing also, so there's a creative writing for us, very much a discussion for us, and so on. I just love science fiction. I don't mind reading an occasional mystery, let's say. I haven't read a Western in 20 years, but I've read lots of science fiction. That's what I like to read, that's what I like to collect. Okay, you also sort of answered this one a minute ago, too. On the weird tales, especially in a few things like this, I have people that I correspond with other collectors and so on, and some of them who can't afford to spend several hundred dollars for some of the early issues, let's say, and might want to read some story that's never been reproduced or something like that, I'll actually make a photocopy of it for them for my expenses and time. And that's one thing I do with some of them. Okay. And you must be fairly knowledgeable about other collectors and the sources and so forth. Are there people who collect the science fiction books simply because it's, oh, I don't know, because it's just something to collect, maybe you're not fans who don't care anything about science fiction? Maybe as an investment, let's say? Because just because something is old doesn't necessarily mean that it's especially valuable. And what would be really difficult from the investor's standpoint, from somebody who knew very little about the field is to know which books to pick up now, because 10 years from now, they're going to be worth a lot. In fact, that's kind of hard for me to guess, and I certainly know more about it than a lot of people do. Well, you're not in it for the investment, are you? No, I'm not, but I'm thinking about comic book collectors especially. There's a heck of a lot of people in that field, while many of the most fanatical ones clearly love comic books, there are people that see this fantastic way that the prices go up on those things and want to buy them just as an investment. In fact, the paperback books are kind of getting in that category to an extent because they are publishing price guides for them now, and they hadn't done that until very recently. In your particular line of collecting, what is considered the ultimate? the ultimate I'd say the rarest item I've got is my volume one, number one, Weird Tales but there are well, it depends on what you're talking about, for example here's an example a lot of people would know about, Frank Herbert's Dune, hardcover the first edition is worth a great deal of money, simply because June wasn't that well known when it first came out. Didn't attract that much attention until slowly over several years. And that first hardcover edition is extremely hard to find. So that in good condition, I understand that a first edition is worth a thousand bucks. Well, I don't have a copy of it. I wouldn't mind having a copy at all, although I wouldn't pay that money for it. But I know somebody who found one in the garage sale in Lubbock. And it bugs the heck out of me. It wasn't me. How much can a really valuable single paperback cost? Well, I can tell you the highest price I've heard anybody charge for anything, and that was, and I don't know that they got it, but this was the asking price, was $175 for Cat and the Canary House by Kurt Vonnegut. I got my copy for $3, I don't mind telling you. What's the most you paid for a paperback? I think about $20. And I don't do that for very many, I assure you. By the way, this isn't a... formal question but do you happen to have a paperback copy of the Hillman edition of The Dying Earth, the first paperback? No, as a matter of fact that's another one that I could have mentioned that's in that pretty good category and Jack Vance in general is a very collectible person and I've got everything that's, say, relatively accessible but I don't have something like that. One thing that I wonder about with paperback and digest collectors like yourself seems to me that paperbacks don't last an awfully long time. How do you store and preserve them for the future? That's a very good question. First of all, they're going to deteriorate no matter what you do. You can slow it down. Here in Lubbock, my stuff is descubering down a basement, and the temperature stays fairly constant, and the humidity is relatively low, and it's not too far from ideal book storage conditions just automatically. The rare things, especially, I do put in plastic bags, and I also have access to, my wife is a librarian up at Texas Tech, and so I have access to her. She's actually the one who does the book repairs, among other things, and all the prepping of books, that sort of thing. So I have access to her facilities for repairing things. If I have a copy glue that say the glue is coming out, I can reglue it with good grade library glue. And I've gotten pretty good at making repairs that are fairly unnoticeable. And I can make a pretty beat up looking copy look halfway decent. That's a lot better to have one that you don't have to do that. If I had a really rare one, I would simply put it in the bag and not touch it anymore and hope it won't crumble. I suppose for something you're buying that's an older copy, no matter what it is, the value is mostly dependent on the condition it's in? The condition is extremely important, yes. You can have a rare book that's in perfect condition and expect to pay anywhere from two to ten times as much as a poorer copy. Because many of the real serious collectors are condition freaks. they won't accept one unless it's just in pretty darn nice shape. Oh, that's easy. Morris J. Ackerman was sort of a number one fan. But anyway, it is reputed to be by far the most fantastic collection that's ever been put together.
